  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "\"Just the meals?\"",
   "count": 1,
   "speaker": "Nameless"
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "\"Six hands' work, five men fed. The sixth eats. That is the whole of it.\"",
   "count": 1,
   "speaker": "Genemon"
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "\"Say nothing.\"",
   "count": 1,
   "speaker": "Nameless"
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "\"Kept, then. The book carries what is claimed, and I keep my own margins.\"",
   "count": 1,
   "speaker": "Genemon"
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "You begin to mark the turning of the days, and the four seasons with them.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "milestone",
   "text": "Rank ↑ — The day-hand 日雇",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "system",
   "text": "You lie down in the bare corner of the woodshed — no mat yet, the woodpile at your back, the cold coming up through the boards. It is somewhere to stop.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "system",
   "text": "You take a bowl of plain rice. (−2 rice)",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "The outer court of the guest house, where the day's work is set out and seen to — set out in the dark now, the days being what they are, and often finished in it. Genemon's lamp is lit before the sky is; what is done here still gets written down.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "The estate's face, kept barely, kept anyway: snow is swept from between the gateposts before anyone can see it lying there. Yohei's stall still comes on market days, smaller, and leaves while there is light to walk home by.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "The outer court of the guest house, where the day's work is set out and seen to — set out in the dark now, the days being what they are, and often finished in it. Genemon's lamp is lit before the sky is; what is done here still gets written down.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "The guest house's skirts, the paddy and the rows that pay for everything else. Winter lays the fields off — stubble, frost, the water let out — and moves their work indoors: the tools that will open them again are mended now or not at all.",
   "count": 1
  },
  {
   "channel": "narration",
   "text": "The weir screens still want keeping whole, and the mending does not wait for a kinder month: bare arms in river water that aches to the bone.",
